WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:06.960
I'm going to be talking about my Shiny app that I created for the 2021 RStudio Shiny Contest,

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:11.440
and I received an honorable mention, which was really exciting. This was basically just a side

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:16.879
project that I started to get a little bit more experience in Shiny, and also to explore a

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:22.240
phenomenon that is special to me, and I'll tell you about that in a moment. So my name is Kaya Gahm,

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.520
and the title of my presentation is Brewing Green Tea, because the app is called Green Tea,

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:34.720
and you'll see why in a moment. So just a little bit about my background. I have a bachelor's in

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:40.639
ecology from Yale, where I studied tadpoles, and this fall I'm going to be starting a PhD at UCLA,

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:46.880
also in ecology and evolutionary biology, studying vultures. So I don't really come from a computer

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:52.400
science background, but I learned to use R in order to analyze ecological data. So I've been

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:58.320
using it for about six years now, and it's pretty much part of my daily routine at this point, but

00:00:58.320 --> 00:01:04.239
I don't come from the sort of front-end web development user-facing side of things really at

00:01:04.239 --> 00:01:10.080
all. So Shiny was pretty new to me this year. For the past year or so, I've been working with the

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:15.839
Cary Institute of Ecosystem Studies as a data manager, and doing a lot of data science basically

00:01:15.839 --> 00:01:21.360
every day, and I had a little bit of spare time this year in between undergrad and grad school,

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:27.360
so I decided to create a Shiny app to explore synesthesia. So for anyone who isn't sure what

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:32.720
this is, synesthesia is a neurological phenomenon where, well there are many different types of

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:38.400
synesthesia, but there's a particular type called grapheme color synesthesia, and in this case

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:45.680
people associate letters or numbers or other sort of graphemes, like characters, with colors in their

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.720
minds. And that doesn't mean, and I have this type of synesthesia, that doesn't mean that I actually

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:57.360
see colors when I see these letters, but I sort of imagine associations between colors and letters.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:03.519
So I'm showing you a few letters of the alphabet here. A is very strongly red for me, B is blue,

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:09.839
C is yellow, D is also blue, but a very distinct shade of blue from B, so you get the idea.

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:16.000
And I have had synesthesia as long as I can remember, and these associations have remained

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.800
constant since I was a kid, and it's just kind of a fun little party trick. It's not, it doesn't

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:25.919
really affect my daily life very much, but when I tell my friends about my synesthesia, they always

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:30.720
want to see my alphabet, they always want to know what color their name is, they want me to show them

00:02:31.279 --> 00:02:38.559
words typed out the way I imagine them in my mind's eye. And this is actually not trivially easy to do

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:43.199
because you have to change the color of every single letter. So for a while I had a Google

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:48.000
doc going where I could copy and paste individual letters to show people what different words would

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:54.720
look like, but that was really clunky and annoying. So then I started Googling to see if there was a

00:02:54.720 --> 00:03:00.080
tool online that would allow me to show people my synesthesia, and I came across this project by

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:07.119
Bernadette Sheridan, where she is also a synesthete, and she created a tool where you can type in any

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:11.839
word, in this case I've entered my name, and you see what it looks like in her synesthesia colors.

00:03:12.559 --> 00:03:18.880
And that's really cool, but it's problematic for me because this looks really wrong to me,

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:23.440
these are the wrong colors. Actually several of them happen to line up with mine, but for example

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:28.720
K is not yellow-green in my head, it's more of a magenta, and so this bothers me and there was no

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:36.080
way to put in my own colors. So I envisioned an app like this where I would have one color

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:42.160
drop-down selector for every single letter of the alphabet and every number, and I'd be able

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:47.919
to set my own colors and have other people set theirs, and then type in my name and have it

00:03:47.919 --> 00:03:53.039
appear in my colors so it actually looks right to me, or type in any other word, and so other

00:03:53.039 --> 00:03:59.919
synesthetes could enter their own colors as well. So I decided to build it in Shiny. Oops, that is

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:09.039
where, hold on just a minute, I think I'm gonna have to reshare my screen in order to show you

00:04:09.039 --> 00:04:21.760
the app, so bear with me just one sec. Okay, so I built the app, and I called it Green Tea because

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:28.320
I wanted some sort of cute little pun, and the letter T is green for me. It initializes with

00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:33.920
a bunch of random colors, but you can set them to my colors, so now everything looks very

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:38.079
satisfying to me because all the letters are the correct colors, and you see this green T here,

00:04:38.079 --> 00:04:42.799
or you can set them all to white and you can pick your own colors if that is what you want to do,

00:04:42.799 --> 00:04:47.839
if you have synesthesia yourself, or if you just want to create a palette. You can download the

00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:55.119
colors as a CSV that downloads their hex codes and their RGB codes as well, and then you can type

00:04:55.119 --> 00:05:01.440
anything you want here. I have it set to type something. I could type my name. You can see

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:06.959
there's a slight delay, and I'll talk about that in a minute. I could type, hi Boston, and it shows

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:12.880
up in my colors, or it shows up in whatever colors you would like to use. You can turn the letters on

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:19.679
and off. You can download the rectangles as a PNG, so those are the images that showed up on my first

00:05:19.679 --> 00:05:25.920
slide were just downloaded from my app, and then I also added some other features. I added an app

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:30.880
where, I'm sorry, a page where you can read more about synesthesia and more about why I developed

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:37.279
this app, and I also have a Google survey mimic page here where you can enter your own information

00:05:37.279 --> 00:05:42.880
optionally, because I was thinking maybe I would do some informal analyses of synesthetes and see

00:05:42.880 --> 00:05:47.760
if I could figure out any patterns, and you can actually submit your own colors, so this listens

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:55.440
to what has been selected on this page and actually contributes it to me as a CSV along with

00:05:55.440 --> 00:06:01.440
your survey responses. So that's just a basic overview of the app itself, but I wanted to talk

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:05.600
in particular about a couple things that came up while developing this Shiny app that were really

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:10.880
fun for me. So I had a little bit of prior experience developing a Shiny app. I actually

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:17.200
developed one this year for work, and it was much more complex than this app and took me a long time.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:24.160
A lot of sort of focused effort all day every day. So by comparison, this app was kind of a breeze.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:30.720
I had a prototype mocked up in just a couple hours, but then I kept going and adding features

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:34.640
and thinking to myself, you know, wouldn't it be cool if it could do this thing? Wouldn't it be cool

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:39.359
if it could do this thing? And I was surprised at how much I could achieve, and so just to call

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:43.359
attention to a couple features here that are a little bit more complicated than they seem.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.679
So first let's look at these rectangles. This, although it might not look like it, is actually a

00:06:49.679 --> 00:06:57.119
ggplot. It looks like just plain rectangles, but it's actually a ggplot with theme void and geom

00:06:57.119 --> 00:07:04.720
rect, if anyone's familiar with ggplot. And behind the scenes, Shiny is listening to the inputs,

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:11.119
the color inputs here, and creating a reactive expression, which is then fed into the ggplot,

00:07:11.119 --> 00:07:15.920
and it remakes the plot every time that there's a change to one of these colors or a change to

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:23.200
one of these letters. So one challenge that I faced with creating this plot is anyone who has

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:29.040
used Shiny before might know that the default with Shiny is that reactive expressions all listen to

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.040
each other all the time. So whenever one of them updates, anything that is listening to that

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:37.839
reactive expression will automatically update pretty much instantaneously. And the challenge

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:42.959
actually comes in preventing that from happening instantaneously or delaying things.

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:49.760
So I was having a problem where every single time I tried to type text, for example, if I typed my

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:57.200
name, it would refresh five times. So you saw that just when I typed that, it basically flashed once.

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:03.040
It showed you the new graph with my name. But before I fixed this, every time I typed a letter,

00:08:03.519 --> 00:08:09.119
the K, the A, the I, the J, the A, it would do what you just saw, except much faster,

00:08:09.119 --> 00:08:12.799
and it looked really chaotic because it was refreshing every single time there was a change.

00:08:13.359 --> 00:08:19.760
So I had to work in a delay where I used the debounce function to only have Shiny listen to

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.440
that reactive expression every fraction of a second so that a reasonable person could

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:31.519
type something relatively quickly and not have the refresh happen on every single letter.

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:36.159
And I want to emphasize that this app absolutely could have existed and could have been functional

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:41.679
without that feature. But tweaking little things like that to improve the user experience was part

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:47.200
of what I really enjoyed about the opportunity to develop this app. Another thing that I would

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:52.960
draw your attention to is this toggle for showing and hiding the letters. And this turned out to be

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:59.520
a pretty simple on off switch where this switch is set to either true or false depending on whether

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:06.080
it's clicked. And the reactive expression that generates the ggplot listens to that and replots

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:12.159
the plot either with or without a geom text layer depending on the position of this switch.

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:16.799
And this was another feature where I had sort of dreamed about it. Wouldn't it be cool? Maybe some

00:09:16.799 --> 00:09:21.039
people prefer it with letters, some people prefer it without letters. And I never thought that it

00:09:21.039 --> 00:09:25.359
would end up being this simple to actually execute. So I was really happy to be able to get this to

00:09:25.359 --> 00:09:31.440
work. One other portion of the app that I want to talk about is these color selectors. There are,

00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:37.119
of course, 36 of them because there's 26 for each letter and then there's 10 for the digits.

00:09:37.119 --> 00:09:44.080
And 36 is a really interesting number because it's few enough that I could type every single one

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:50.000
manually to create the selectors. I could have 36 lines of code where I create the A, create the B,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.320
create the C, create the D. And that's how I started the app because I just wanted to get it

00:09:54.320 --> 00:10:00.799
mocked up really quickly. I could copy and paste. No big deal. But 36 is also a large enough number

00:10:01.359 --> 00:10:07.599
that doing something 36 times starts to be annoying after a while. And so this was a great

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:14.559
opportunity for me to incrementally develop my app to move toward better practices in Shiny

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:20.000
app development. So I started with a lot of repeated lines of code. And gradually, gradually,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.280
I streamlined everything, made it slightly more efficient until ultimately I ended up

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:30.159
at a structure where I wrote a function that would generate each of these color selectors

00:10:30.159 --> 00:10:35.840
and then I applied that function 36 times, feeding in the input IDs and the display text

00:10:36.479 --> 00:10:42.559
and the starting colors each time. And that was, again, really satisfying. And this app, once again,

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:46.960
could have existed, could have been functional without that sort of behind the scenes improvement,

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:53.679
but it was very satisfying to be able to sort of streamline all of that. So those are just a few

00:10:53.679 --> 00:10:59.440
of the features in this app. I could go on. I wrote a blog post highlighting a couple of the

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:03.280
challenges like that that were sort of fun to tackle that made the app what it is today.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.479
And I'm going to provide a link to that blog post if anybody's interested in seeing my code

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:13.520
or interested in reading about the other stuff. But I wanted to just take a moment to reflect on

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:19.440
some general lessons that I took away from this app for developing Shiny apps in general. And the

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:24.960
first thing, which I've alluded to during this talk, is to start simple and then build up and

00:11:24.960 --> 00:11:30.080
really don't be afraid to dream about what you'd like to see in the app and then try to make it

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:35.200
happen. This definitely might not be true for everybody, but at least for me, I'm very much

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:40.559
a person who learns best when I have a defined goal and a problem to solve and then I have to

00:11:40.559 --> 00:11:45.840
figure out how to do it. So I did watch some Shiny tutorials when I was first starting out,

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:50.080
but I didn't just sit down with a textbook and try to teach myself Shiny in a vacuum.

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:55.200
I taught myself the bare bones. I made a bare bones app and then I thought to myself, you know,

00:11:55.200 --> 00:12:00.479
what would I like to see and how can I make it happen with really no regard to whether the feature

00:12:00.479 --> 00:12:06.000
I was trying to develop was appropriate for beginners or whether it was, you know, something

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.039
I should be working on? Just is it something I want to work on and can I read enough help docs

00:12:11.039 --> 00:12:16.239
and get enough help from my peers and whatnot and just figure out how to make it happen?

00:12:16.239 --> 00:12:21.119
And that was extremely rewarding and that's really how I got to have this app where it is today.

00:12:21.119 --> 00:12:26.320
And it's a surprisingly successful process, at least for me, is to just go intramentally like that.

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:33.919
And the second tip that I have for people is it was very useful for me to debug via video chat

00:12:33.919 --> 00:12:39.280
with willing friends or collaborators. In my case, it was people I met on the R for Data Science

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:44.000
Slack channel. So I reached out to a couple people who were working on their own Shiny apps and had

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:50.559
them sort of at a stage of development. And we set up some video chat calls where I helped the person

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:57.280
debug their app and then they helped me debug my app. And it was really refreshing and really

00:12:57.280 --> 00:13:01.840
helpful to be able to show people in real time what was going wrong and to be able to help them

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:08.000
in real time with their problems. And that was that helped me a lot and I got some great ideas

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.320
by talking to other people. So if you have the opportunity to set up a collaboration like that,

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:17.039
I think that can be a great way to learn Shiny. So I'll stop now because I know we don't have a

00:13:17.039 --> 00:13:21.840
lot of time, but I would welcome any questions and I will share some more resources in my slides at

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:30.640
the end. Thank you. Awesome. Thank you so much, Kaya. I don't see any questions yet in the chat,

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:34.559
so feel free to ask live as well if anyone has any questions.

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:47.280
Kaya, something that I was curious about is for like the actual, like when you first made

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:51.679
this application, did you use some sort of template or you just started from the beginning

00:13:52.799 --> 00:13:57.679
like Shiny app example? No, I started from the beginning and it looked really ugly.

00:13:57.679 --> 00:14:04.559
I knew I wanted the selectors sort of in a section and I knew that I wanted to get them

00:14:04.559 --> 00:14:11.119
into some sort of grid. And I think I used some combination of fluid row, fluid page, columns,

00:14:11.119 --> 00:14:15.919
rows. I think initially I just had them all in one column and of course it looked really stupid

00:14:15.919 --> 00:14:21.039
and it was really, really long, but you know, it worked and I could see that that was functional.

00:14:21.039 --> 00:14:26.479
And then I gradually tweaked the UI. I figured I, it was sort of this interesting tug of war

00:14:26.479 --> 00:14:31.760
between not wanting to focus too much on UI design from the beginning, but also it's just

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:37.359
hard to look at something that looks really bad. And I wanted to have everything sort of,

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:42.799
you know, compact enough that I could, that I could reasonably work on developing it.

00:14:42.799 --> 00:14:48.640
Yeah. Cool. James, I see you had a question in the chat. Do you want to ask it live?

00:14:49.599 --> 00:14:55.200
Sure. Yeah, that, that I found the time delay feature you included kind of interesting. Could

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:59.440
you expand on that a little bit? I didn't, I missed the package you used.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.280
Yeah. This was a fun one because I, so I've, in the past I've written apps where there's like a

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:10.799
submit button or something where I think the, the reactive inputs respond only when a button is

00:15:10.799 --> 00:15:14.239
clicked or something like that. So I was thinking about doing that, but I actually wanted this one

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:20.479
to be more responsive in real time and to have a little bit less user input. So I was trying and

00:15:20.479 --> 00:15:25.440
trying to figure this out. And I had, I was talking to somebody on R for Data Science about

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:30.880
this whole approach that I had mapped out that involved some reactive values and some, I don't

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:35.520
even remember what was behind the scenes. And he said, Oh, do you know about the debounce function?

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:40.239
And I was like, no, I don't know about the debounce function. So the debounce function

00:15:40.239 --> 00:15:46.000
is, I'm actually, is it a native Shiny function? I'm checking right now. Yeah. So it's just a

00:15:46.559 --> 00:15:54.320
function right in Shiny and it throttles the code in the background on the server a little bit.

00:15:54.320 --> 00:16:00.080
And you can specify how much to slow it down. So in my case, I just had a reactive expression

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:05.440
that was the data frame that was going to get passed into the GG plot. And I just piped that

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:11.200
data frame into the debounce function and specified, I think it was 25 milliseconds or

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:18.080
something like that. And that just means that instead of checking for updates to the reactive

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:25.440
expression as fast as Shiny possibly can, it will only check every 25, whatever, every, I don't know

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:29.919
exactly the details, but it checks only every so often. And I just basically played around with

00:16:29.919 --> 00:16:35.200
that until it updated still fast enough that it seemed like it was responding to the user input,

00:16:35.200 --> 00:16:38.960
but slow enough that it wouldn't have to flash every single time you entered a letter.

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:44.719
Yeah. So debounce is the function. And so that was a function of how quickly someone

00:16:44.719 --> 00:16:52.960
was typing the letters in? Yeah. So because each, the, the object in,

00:16:53.840 --> 00:17:01.760
hang on, I'll share again. So this text to display right here, this was an input, a text input. And so

00:17:01.760 --> 00:17:08.160
every time this text input changed, I took that text input, I transformed it into a data frame

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:12.959
that then got fed into the GG plot. And so every time that data frame was updated,

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:17.520
the plot would refresh. And so anytime that somebody was typing,

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:22.640
you know, this is a different entry, this is a different entry, et cetera. Yeah. And you can see

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:28.239
when I type really slowly, it does update every single time, but it takes just a little while.

00:17:28.239 --> 00:17:35.680
And if I write something really long, it'll show it all at once like this, because I type

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:40.400
relatively fast, whereas before it was this horrible chaos of flashing colors until you

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:44.800
finally got to the end. And so that's kind of the way that it works.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:50.880
Thank you. I see you, there was one other question from Robert Klein. Do you want to ask that one live as well?

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:02.400
Or I can read it too. Robert asked earlier, can you read from the colors on their own?

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:08.079
Hmm. Not really, because there are a bunch that are similar, but there are a bunch that are

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:15.760
on their own. Hmm. Not really, because there are a bunch that are similar. I have a lot of greens

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:21.680
and browns, but I can't, especially with the numbers, because the numbers are all really

00:18:21.680 --> 00:18:27.359
distinct. There aren't any that are similar at all. And so that's very useful for memorizing,

00:18:27.359 --> 00:18:33.280
like bank account numbers or credit card numbers or, you know, pins, for example. I have a couple

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:38.640
pins that, you know, I would never remember the sequence of numbers, but it's some logical, it

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:45.280
like goes well together. And so I remember it. So if you really pressed me, I could probably

00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:49.439
figure stuff out, but it would be a lot harder with the alphabet than with the numbers.

00:18:53.359 --> 00:19:00.160
Awesome. Thank you so much, Kaia. That was great. And if anyone else is interested, maybe in the

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:05.199
future, I know they have the Shiny contest every year, and I'll put the blog post where I learned

00:19:05.199 --> 00:19:10.800
about Kaia's app in the chat, too. But thank you so much for the presentation. That was great.

00:19:12.239 --> 00:19:17.280
Thank you for having me. If there are any other questions, too, feel free to put them in the chat

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:22.800
as well and maybe put Kaia's name on them, and then we could save them for the end, too. But

